<td width="100%" class="title"><font face="Verdana,Arial,helvetica,sans-serif" size="4" color="#0d4d9b"><b>2000 International CES Attracts Record Number of Top Government Officials</b></font></td>
</tr>
</table>

	
	



	
	<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0">
	
	<tr>
	
		<td width="18"><img src="/Graphics/Interface/Icons/spacer.gif" width=18 height=1 border=0></td>
	
	
		<td>
	




	<font size="-1"><b>Congressmen Berman, Bliley, Ehrlich, Luther and Tauzin, FCC Chairman Kennard and Other Officials to Speak at CES</b></font>

	<p>Arlington, VA - Dec, 15 1999
	<BR>
	More than 40 key public officials will represent the U.S. federal and state governments at the <b>2000 International CES-Your Source for Workstyle and Lifestyle Technology</b>, in Las Vegas, Nev., January 6-9, 2000.  Representatives from Capitol Hill, the White House, the Department of Commerce, the Federal Communications Commission (FCC), the Federal Trade Commission (FTC), the State of Virginia and the U.S. International Trade Commission will be at CES.   Several government attendees also will participate in conference sessions specifically designed to educate the industry on the ways in which business and government can work together.  <P>
 "CES is the world's leading source for the latest consumer technology information," said Gary Shapiro, president and CEO of the Consumer Electronics Association (CEA).  "Among the more than 90,000 international industry professionals expected at CES, are the top government officials who come to Vegas to learn about what's new and hot for consumers' workstyles and lifestyles.  CES allows the consumer technology industry to build an important relationship with the public sector that facilitates communications throughout the year." <P>
 In a CES Special Luncheon Session on Friday, January 7 at 11:45am in LVCC N259, William E. Kennard, chairman of the FCC, will address the consumer technology industry.   <P>
 Virginia Governor James Gilmore, chairman of the Advisory Committee on E-Commerce, will host Internet 2000, a half-day summit on the Internet's impact on American society in the new millennium.  Several invited technology leaders and government officials will join him to discuss ways to enhance opportunities created by the Internet.  The session will address several critical issues, such as taxes, encryption, privacy and the challenge of attracting, educating and maintaining a highly trained workforce.  Speakers will include House Commerce Committee Chairman Rep. Thomas Bliley (R-Va.), FCC Commissioner Susan Ness and industry executives John Chambers, president and CEO, Cisco; Brad Chase, senior vice president, e-commerce, Microsoft; John Roth, vice chairman and COO, Nortel; and Bill Schrader, CEO, PSINet.  Internet 2000 runs from 1:00-4:15pm on Friday, January 7 in the Las Vegas Hilton Theater. <P>
 Several government and industry officials, including Rep. Robert Ehrlich (R-Md.); FTC Commissioner Mozelle W. Thompson; Eileen Harrington, Bureau of Consumer Protection, FTC; Russ Bodoff, BBBOnLine; and Monica Azare, chief counsel, Office of the House Telecommunications Subcommittee Chairman Rep. Billy Tauzin (R-La.), will participate in an Online Privacy Panel moderated by Mike Feazel of <i>Communications Daily</i>.  The panel will provide information about "fair information practices" and government monitoring of the progress of self-regulation by industry.  <P>
 In addition to Internet 2000 and the Online Privacy Panel, Paul Misener, former chief counsel to FCC Commissioner Furchtgott-Roth, will moderate "Broadband: Is Government Action Needed to Ensure Open Competition".  Along with Rep. Tauzin; Rep. Howard Berman (D-Calif.), House Judiciary Committee; and Peter Pitsch, Intel's communications policy director, Misener will discuss the advent of broadband technologies into America's homes. <P>
 Another session, "Do You Know How Washington Affects the Consumer Electronics Business", will teach attendees how to track what's happening in Washington.  Moderated by Gary Klein, CEA's vice president of government and legal affairs, government panelists will include Rep. Ehrlich; Rep. Bill Luther (D-Minn.), House Commerce Committee; Tony Rudy, deputy chief of staff, Office of the House Majority Whip Tom DeLay (R-Texas); Jim Barker, chief of staff, Office of Sen. Robert F. Bennett (R-Utah); and Azare.  <P>
 During "Tapping into the Billion-Dollar Government Market," CES attendees can hear from Commissioner Frank P. Pugliese Jr., Federal Supply Service, General Services Administration; Bill Howell, senior vice president and tradeshow group manager, Post-Newsweek Business Information Inc.; and Thomas Temin, editorial director, <i>Government Computer News</i>.  The U.S. government is the largest buyer of technology in the world-everything from paging and cellular products and services, to PDAs, to home office products.   <P>
 FTC Commissioner Orson Swindle will address CEA's Government Affairs Council meeting on Friday, January 7.  The government affairs activities at CES are topped off with a private dinner for government officials and industry CEOs at the Bellagio on Friday, January 7.  Eric Benhamou, chairman and chief executive officer of 3Com Corp., will be the featured speaker at the dinner. <P>
 CEA is a sector of the Electronic Industries Alliance (EIA), the 75-year-old Arlington, Virginia-based trade organization representing all facets of electronics manufacturing.  CEA represents more than 500 U.S. manufacturers of audio, video, accessories, mobile electronics, communication, information technology and multimedia products that are sold through consumer channels.   <P>
 CEA also sponsors and manages the International CES, the world's largest annual trade event showcasing consumer technologies.  All profits from CES are reinvested into industry services, including technical training and education, product promotion, engineering standards development, market research, and governmental and legal affairs support.  As the first major technology event of the new millennium, the 2000 International CES is the launch pad for 21st century technology.  <P>
	<BR>&nbsp;<BR>&nbsp;
	

		
